1
00:00:01,675 --> 00:00:04,508
(Multicom Jingle)

2
00:00:25,496 --> 00:00:28,246
(tinkling music)

3
00:01:12,066 --> 00:01:14,816
(waves crashing)

4
00:01:25,129 --> 00:01:28,046
(light jazz music)

5
00:02:31,207 --> 00:02:32,916
- [Marilyn] When I was
born in the charity ward

6
00:02:32,916 --> 00:02:37,521
of the Los Angeles County
Hospital, my mother wasn't there.

7
00:02:37,521 --> 00:02:40,271
Where my mother was, no one knew.

8
00:02:41,930 --> 00:02:44,392
- Mrs. Mortenson, are you in here?

9
00:02:44,392 --> 00:02:46,809
(baby cries)

10
00:02:48,732 --> 00:02:49,565
Shh.

11
00:02:54,170 --> 00:02:55,070
Mrs. Mortenson?

12
00:02:58,790 --> 00:03:00,740
Mrs. Mortenson, is that you back there?

13
00:03:02,390 --> 00:03:04,540
We've been searching
all over the hospital.

14
00:03:06,900 --> 00:03:08,200
Aren't you even gonna have a look

15
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:09,700
at your beautiful little girl?

16
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:16,010
Please, Mrs. Mortenson,
you can't stay in here.

17
00:03:17,116 --> 00:03:19,900
(baby crying)

18
00:03:19,900 --> 00:03:21,490
This is one sweet baby.

19
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:24,140
- Am I really the mother?

20
00:03:24,140 --> 00:03:25,690
- Of course you're the mother.

21
00:03:25,690 --> 00:03:27,040
I helped with the delivery.

22
00:03:28,770 --> 00:03:29,760
Come on now.

23
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:34,014
- But what if I drop it?

24
00:03:34,014 --> 00:03:36,480
(baby crying)

25
00:03:36,480 --> 00:03:39,040
Oh, it's so hot,

26
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:40,410
and heavy.

27
00:03:40,410 --> 00:03:42,190
- She's a normal, healthy baby.

28
00:03:43,740 --> 00:03:44,573
A beauty.

29
00:03:45,590 --> 00:03:46,540
Look at those eyes.

30
00:03:48,619 --> 00:03:52,330
- Hell, kid wasn't half
bad-looking, I decided to keep her.

31
00:03:53,410 --> 00:03:55,920
I named her Norma, after Norma Talmadge,

32
00:03:57,120 --> 00:03:59,240
and Jeane after Jean Harlow.

33
00:04:00,560 --> 00:04:02,250
Norma Jeane Baker.

34
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:05,590
Baker's not her father, but he's

35
00:04:05,590 --> 00:04:06,900
the husband I hated the least.

36
00:04:07,874 --> 00:04:09,660
(laughs)

37
00:04:09,660 --> 00:04:10,493
- Oh!

38
00:04:11,881 --> 00:04:13,700
Oh my goodness.

39
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:14,750
Oh!

40
00:04:14,750 --> 00:04:17,350
Oh, honey, now listen.

41
00:04:17,350 --> 00:04:21,390
Do you remember what I
told you, Norma Jeane,

42
00:04:21,390 --> 00:04:23,580
when you're with your mother, watch out

43
00:04:23,580 --> 00:04:25,696
for those changes of moods?

44
00:04:25,696 --> 00:04:27,340
- I do, Grandma.

45
00:04:27,340 --> 00:04:29,230
I always do what you say.

46
00:04:29,230 --> 00:04:30,880
- Well if you think that
it's getting dangerous,

47
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:33,900
I want you to run to a
telephone and call me.

48
00:04:34,780 --> 00:04:36,550
I will go and I will get a taxi cab

49
00:04:36,550 --> 00:04:39,560
and I don't even care if it's $5,

50
00:04:39,560 --> 00:04:40,880
I'm gonna come and get you.

51
00:04:40,880 --> 00:04:42,876
Will you remember?

52
00:04:42,876 --> 00:04:44,880
- I'll remember.

53
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:46,050
- Oh, look, look, look.

54
00:04:46,050 --> 00:04:47,000
See that tough guy?

55
00:04:47,912 --> 00:04:50,120
A regular Jimmy Cagney.

56
00:04:50,120 --> 00:04:53,750
Now that is a movie star I really like.

57
00:04:54,710 --> 00:04:56,280
A real man.

58
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:58,310
He knows when his number's up.

59
00:04:59,303 --> 00:05:00,970
- What about that one?

60
00:05:00,970 --> 00:05:02,050
- That one.

61
00:05:02,050 --> 00:05:03,470
That one is Mary Pickford.

62
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:05,930
America's sweetheart.

63
00:05:07,343 --> 00:05:12,343
- Oh Grandma, where do
they go when they fly away?

64
00:05:14,091 --> 00:05:16,868
- I don't know.

65
00:05:16,868 --> 00:05:18,537
China!

66
00:05:18,537 --> 00:05:21,420
- Let's go to China, fly with me!

67
00:05:21,420 --> 00:05:22,253
Come on!

68
00:05:24,516 --> 00:05:27,870
- My crazy daughter was
unfit to be a mother.

69
00:05:27,870 --> 00:05:31,140
I took Norma Jeane when
she was just a baby.

70
00:05:32,530 --> 00:05:36,750
I wanted to adopt her, give
her my last name, Monroe.

71
00:05:38,092 --> 00:05:41,110
But Gladys wouldn't let me.

72
00:05:41,110 --> 00:05:41,943
Oh no.

73
00:05:41,943 --> 00:05:42,930
- Norma Jeane, come.

74
00:05:42,930 --> 00:05:46,130
- [Della] She preferred to board her out.

75
00:05:46,130 --> 00:05:49,050
- Norma Jeane, my love,
come come come, come.

76
00:05:49,050 --> 00:05:52,870
- [Della] Paid me $5 a week plus expenses.

77
00:05:52,870 --> 00:05:53,920
- Your birthday.

78
00:05:53,920 --> 00:05:57,330
I will not be deprived of
mother love on this special day.

79
00:05:58,690 --> 00:06:00,320
Oh.

80
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:01,640
- Wait.

81
00:06:01,640 --> 00:06:02,473
Wait.

82
00:06:04,182 --> 00:06:06,610
Tell me something, what
have you been smoking?

83
00:06:08,020 --> 00:06:09,180
Look at me, girl.

84
00:06:11,783 --> 00:06:12,683
Are you hopped up?

85
00:06:13,560 --> 00:06:16,200
- I've never even smelled
marijuana, let alone smoked it.

86
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:18,040
And that goes double for opium.

87
00:06:19,800 --> 00:06:20,633
Never.

88
00:06:22,250 --> 00:06:23,083
- [Della] Wait!

89
00:06:23,083 --> 00:06:25,940
- Rain or shine, sickness or in health,

90
00:06:25,940 --> 00:06:29,230
till death do us part, I vow.

91
00:06:30,932 --> 00:06:31,890
There you go, baby.

92
00:06:31,890 --> 00:06:34,600
- When will you be getting
my granddaughter back?

93
00:06:34,600 --> 00:06:35,810
- Ignore your grandmother, dear,

94
00:06:35,810 --> 00:06:39,580
she's silent film and we are talkies.

95
00:06:42,048 --> 00:06:44,196
(upbeat jazz music)

96
00:06:44,196 --> 00:06:46,613
(horn honks)

97
00:06:54,324 --> 00:06:56,741
(horn honks)

98
00:07:01,163 --> 00:07:04,330
(children chattering)

99
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:07,300
My new neighborhood.

100
00:07:08,316 --> 00:07:10,166
And only six minutes from the studio.

101
00:07:11,040 --> 00:07:13,400
I have a surprise for you, birthday girl.

102
00:07:13,400 --> 00:07:14,233
Let's go.

103
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:18,510
There's someone waiting and
he might be getting impatient.

104
00:07:22,130 --> 00:07:22,963
Voila!

105
00:07:25,313 --> 00:07:27,480
(panting)

106
00:07:34,280 --> 00:07:36,304
(sighs)

107
00:07:36,304 --> 00:07:39,950
Well let's see, where could
our special someone be?

108
00:07:39,950 --> 00:07:42,920
Very cold, you're cold,
you're cold, you're cold.

109
00:07:45,730 --> 00:07:46,563
Getting warmer.

110
00:07:47,580 --> 00:07:49,670
Oh, come on, come on, in here.

111
00:07:51,751 --> 00:07:52,990
Hmm?

112
00:07:56,220 --> 00:07:57,930
Oh, Norma Jeane.

113
00:07:58,850 --> 00:08:00,770
I swear, sometimes I think you're blind.

114
00:08:01,770 --> 00:08:02,660
Open your eyes.

115
00:08:04,090 --> 00:08:04,923
Don't you see?

116
00:08:06,260 --> 00:08:07,093
No?

117
00:08:07,990 --> 00:08:10,390
This man is your father.

118
00:08:11,820 --> 00:08:13,420
- My father?

119
00:08:13,420 --> 00:08:14,533
- Yes.

120
00:08:14,533 --> 00:08:15,620
What'd you think, you didn't have one?

121
00:08:16,956 --> 00:08:19,130
Oh, it's a beautiful
name, an important name,

122
00:08:19,130 --> 00:08:23,130
but a name I can't utter, even
Grandma Della doesn't know.

123
00:08:25,070 --> 00:08:26,110
- Where is he?

124
00:08:26,110 --> 00:08:27,450
- Away.

125
00:08:27,450 --> 00:08:29,164
At a great distance.

126
00:08:29,164 --> 00:08:32,850
He's risked his life in
the name of democracy.

127
00:08:34,560 --> 00:08:39,080
But someday, he will return
to Los Angeles to claim you.

128
00:08:43,960 --> 00:08:46,650
Happy birthday, Norma Jeane.

129
00:08:46,650 --> 00:08:49,580
Didn't I tell you this
would be your special day?

130
00:08:49,580 --> 00:08:52,270
Oh yes, yes, I have a dress for you.

131
00:08:52,270 --> 00:08:53,390
Beautiful, satin.

132
00:08:54,500 --> 00:08:55,900
You'll look like a princess.

133
00:08:57,500 --> 00:08:59,124
Too short?

134
00:08:59,124 --> 00:09:04,085
Well, go on, try it on.

135
00:09:04,085 --> 00:09:07,190
Hophead bastard of a baker.

136
00:09:07,190 --> 00:09:08,550
Spelled birthday wrong.

137
00:09:09,620 --> 00:09:10,453
And your name.

138
00:09:11,410 --> 00:09:12,243
I told him.

139
00:09:13,486 --> 00:09:16,470
(upbeat jazz music)

140
00:09:16,470 --> 00:09:17,303
Norma Jeane.

141
00:09:18,880 --> 00:09:20,400
You must make a wish.

142
00:09:20,400 --> 00:09:24,800
A wish to make you know
who return to us soon.

143
00:09:26,210 --> 00:09:27,393
Go on, go on.

144
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,167
(blowing)

145
00:09:32,764 --> 00:09:34,804
(laughing)

146
00:09:34,804 --> 00:09:36,404
There you are, good as a prayer.

147
00:09:43,020 --> 00:09:45,051
Well, don't be scared.

148
00:09:45,051 --> 00:09:50,051
Only gonna cut the cake.

149
00:09:52,690 --> 00:09:54,430
(water running)

150
00:09:54,430 --> 00:09:55,263
Shame on you.

151
00:09:56,140 --> 00:09:57,560
Oh, shame, the cake!

152
00:09:58,770 --> 00:10:00,620
Cake all over you.

153
00:10:01,700 --> 00:10:02,533
Oh.

154
00:10:04,355 --> 00:10:05,800
Do you do these things deliberately?

155
00:10:07,024 --> 00:10:08,274
- No, I didn't.

156
00:10:09,464 --> 00:10:11,090
- Well who did, Santa Claus?

157
00:10:11,090 --> 00:10:12,840
Don't you know that I borrowed this dress

158
00:10:12,840 --> 00:10:14,820
from the studio and now it's ruined?

159
00:10:14,820 --> 00:10:16,640
Where do you think clothes come from?

160
00:10:16,640 --> 00:10:18,340
You think they just grow on trees?

161
00:10:19,428 --> 00:10:20,261
Sit, sit!

162
00:10:21,424 --> 00:10:23,508
- It's kind of hot.

163
00:10:23,508 --> 00:10:24,704
Mother!

164
00:10:24,704 --> 00:10:26,920
- No, sit still.

165
00:10:26,920 --> 00:10:27,935
Where is the soap?

166
00:10:27,935 --> 00:10:29,328
Soap.

167
00:10:29,328 --> 00:10:32,350
So much dirt, outside of us and in.

168
00:10:34,350 --> 00:10:39,215
Hope is the thing with feathers
that perches in the soul

169
00:10:39,215 --> 00:10:42,510
and sings the tune without the words,

170
00:10:42,510 --> 00:10:44,220
and never stops at all.

171
00:10:46,420 --> 00:10:50,590
Emily Dickinson, that's
so lovely, isn't it?

172
00:10:50,590 --> 00:10:54,080
Hope is the thing with feathers
that perches in the soul.

173
00:10:56,975 --> 00:11:01,975
I always wanted to be a
poet, like Emily Dickinson or

174
00:11:02,240 --> 00:11:06,900
Edna St. Vincent Millay.

175
00:11:06,900 --> 00:11:08,370
I have the soul of a poet.

176
00:11:10,120 --> 00:11:14,200
Of course, I was an
actress once, you know.

177
00:11:14,200 --> 00:11:17,020
I just trasnferred to another department.

178
00:11:21,670 --> 00:11:23,300
Maybe you'll be my poet.

179
00:11:28,624 --> 00:11:30,590
What's wrong with me?

180
00:11:30,590 --> 00:11:32,390
I can't believe it, I almost forgot.

181
00:11:33,935 --> 00:11:36,990
I have another present
for the birthday girl.

182
00:11:36,990 --> 00:11:39,270
Come on.

183
00:11:40,740 --> 00:11:41,573
Ta da.

184
00:11:46,810 --> 00:11:48,620
Norma Jeane, do you remember who

185
00:11:48,620 --> 00:11:50,640
used to sleep in this drawer?

186
00:11:50,640 --> 00:11:53,480
In this very drawer, you
remember who slept here?

187
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:54,640
You.

188
00:11:54,640 --> 00:11:55,980
You, Norma Jeane.

189
00:11:57,348 --> 00:11:59,810
I was so poor I couldn't afford a crib.

190
00:12:01,240 --> 00:12:02,540
This drawer was your crib.

191
00:12:06,964 --> 00:12:10,047
(somber piano music)

192
00:12:35,915 --> 00:12:36,998
Sweet dreams.

193
00:12:55,289 --> 00:12:56,122
- Daddy.

194
00:12:58,409 --> 00:12:59,765
Daddy.

195
00:12:59,765 --> 00:13:03,170
It would be said of me that
I was unhappy as a child,

196
00:13:03,170 --> 00:13:07,485
that my childhood was a desperate one,

197
00:13:07,485 --> 00:13:10,080
but let me tell you, I was never unhappy.

198
00:13:11,390 --> 00:13:14,100
So long as I had my mother,
I was never unhappy.

199
00:13:16,920 --> 00:13:21,920
And my father, well,
I had a picture of him

200
00:13:23,750 --> 00:13:28,485
forever etched in my mind.

201
00:13:28,485 --> 00:13:30,735
(laughing)

202
00:13:32,491 --> 00:13:33,658
- Norma Jeane?

203
00:13:35,865 --> 00:13:36,865
Norma Jeane!

204
00:13:38,505 --> 00:13:40,245
- Here she comes.

205
00:13:40,245 --> 00:13:41,078
That old fat elephant.

206
00:13:42,557 --> 00:13:43,390
Let's run.

207
00:13:48,896 --> 00:13:50,599
She don't see us.

208
00:13:50,599 --> 00:13:54,500
- Norma Jeane!

209
00:13:54,500 --> 00:13:57,617
Norma Jeane.

210
00:13:57,617 --> 00:14:00,200
(wind blowing)

211
00:14:02,157 --> 00:14:04,907
(birds chirping)

212
00:14:15,050 --> 00:14:16,060
- Grandma, I'm home!

213
00:14:18,790 --> 00:14:19,623
Grandma?

214
00:14:24,504 --> 00:14:25,337
(gasps) Grandma!

215
00:14:27,412 --> 00:14:29,662
(coughing)

216
00:14:32,713 --> 00:14:35,796
(Norma Jeane crying)

217
00:14:42,189 --> 00:14:43,939
- I love you so much.

218
00:14:47,029 --> 00:14:49,240
- It was my fault she died.

219
00:14:49,240 --> 00:14:50,840
I wouldn't come when she called.

220
00:14:51,804 --> 00:14:52,637
I was bad.

221
00:14:54,829 --> 00:14:57,320
- Look, it was God's fault.

222
00:15:01,327 --> 00:15:02,160
Now, go to bed.

223
00:15:04,644 --> 00:15:06,230
I have to get up early in the morning.

224
00:15:08,424 --> 00:15:09,580
(sighs)

225
00:15:09,580 --> 00:15:10,413
- Mother.

226
00:15:11,670 --> 00:15:12,620
Can she hear us?

227
00:15:13,680 --> 00:15:14,680
Can Grandma hear us?

228
00:15:15,590 --> 00:15:16,423
- I hope not.

229
00:15:17,799 --> 00:15:19,340
- It was my fault.

230
00:15:19,340 --> 00:15:20,720
Oh Mommy.

231
00:15:20,720 --> 00:15:22,170
- Don't call me Mommy.

232
00:15:22,170 --> 00:15:24,920
I just, I hate those pukey cute titles.

233
00:15:26,809 --> 00:15:28,892
(crying)

234
00:15:30,780 --> 00:15:31,613
Look.

235
00:15:33,980 --> 00:15:36,490
Your grandma's number came up is all.

236
00:15:37,890 --> 00:15:39,690
You don't go until your number's up.

237
00:15:41,070 --> 00:15:42,390
That's why I'm a fatalist.

238
00:15:43,340 --> 00:15:44,490
Can't argue with logic.

239
00:15:47,977 --> 00:15:50,227
(coughing)

240
00:15:54,488 --> 00:15:55,405
This cough.

241
00:15:56,388 --> 00:15:57,471
My hands too.

242
00:15:58,913 --> 00:16:01,263
The chemicals in the film
lab are stronger now.

243
00:16:03,592 --> 00:16:05,380
My eyes, my lungs.

244
00:16:07,390 --> 00:16:09,080
My job is killing me.

245
00:16:15,592 --> 00:16:17,920
You know what you have to
do after school tomorrow?

246
00:16:17,920 --> 00:16:19,700
- Walk to the movie?

247
00:16:19,700 --> 00:16:21,250
- Sit at the back on the aisle.

248
00:16:22,570 --> 00:16:23,990
Don't sit too close to men.

249
00:16:25,692 --> 00:16:28,610
- But see, they keep sitting by me.

250
00:16:29,650 --> 00:16:30,730
- You're not listening.

251
00:16:32,310 --> 00:16:36,830
On the way home, walk on the
curb under the street light.

252
00:16:37,912 --> 00:16:39,920
That way you'll be seen if
anybody tries to grab you.

253
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:43,928
(coughing)

254
00:16:43,928 --> 00:16:45,920
Don't tell anybody about
these movie days, all right?

255
00:16:47,370 --> 00:16:48,370
I have to work late.

256
00:16:49,320 --> 00:16:52,830
There are tasks in developing
that only I can do.

257
00:16:54,428 --> 00:16:55,261
I mustn't fail.

258
00:16:56,460 --> 00:16:58,760
They would fire me, and
that would be the end.

259
00:17:03,710 --> 00:17:05,000
I'm not a bad mother.

260
00:17:06,330 --> 00:17:09,820
I coulda put you in an
orphanage and I didn't, did I?

261
00:17:09,820 --> 00:17:10,910
- Mommy!

262
00:17:10,910 --> 00:17:11,743
- Oh, damn.

263
00:17:16,584 --> 00:17:17,452
(sighs)

264
00:17:17,452 --> 00:17:18,285
What next?

265
00:17:20,108 --> 00:17:22,957
(somber music)

266
00:17:22,957 --> 00:17:24,308
- [Woman] Hello darling.

267
00:17:24,308 --> 00:17:25,247
- [Man] Vera.

268
00:17:25,247 --> 00:17:27,350
How did you happen to come?

269
00:17:27,350 --> 00:17:28,580
- [Woman] Just passin' by.

270
00:17:29,932 --> 00:17:32,307
I wanted to rub my nose against your door.

271
00:17:35,140 --> 00:17:37,010
- And then the fairy princess died,

272
00:17:37,010 --> 00:17:38,980
she had golden hair and it was spread out

273
00:17:38,980 --> 00:17:40,730
all over her pillow.

274
00:17:40,730 --> 00:17:42,014
- That was the end?

275
00:17:42,014 --> 00:17:42,870
Huh.

276
00:17:42,870 --> 00:17:44,760
The dark prince was long
gone by then, I suppose.

277
00:17:44,760 --> 00:17:46,060
Careful, careful, careful.

278
00:17:47,313 --> 00:17:49,790
- No, no, the dark prince loved her.

279
00:17:49,790 --> 00:17:52,120
He was standing over her, crying.

280
00:17:53,030 --> 00:17:54,510
I don't want her to die.

281
00:17:54,510 --> 00:17:55,490
- That's because you understand

282
00:17:55,490 --> 00:17:57,470
how important it is to stay alive.

283
00:17:57,470 --> 00:17:58,883
- Easy.

284
00:17:58,883 --> 00:18:00,050
(grunts)

285
00:18:00,050 --> 00:18:01,010
- Be careful, boys.

286
00:18:01,010 --> 00:18:02,420
Fredrick March gave me this piano

287
00:18:02,420 --> 00:18:04,270
and I don't want it to get scratched.

288
00:18:05,337 --> 00:18:06,514
(man chuckles)

289
00:18:06,514 --> 00:18:09,230
Your father would be
so jealous if he knew.

290
00:18:11,090 --> 00:18:12,140
I have plans for you.

291
00:18:13,870 --> 00:18:14,790
For us.

292
00:18:15,728 --> 00:18:19,330
(upbeat jazz music)

293
00:18:19,330 --> 00:18:20,470
Ah, there, you see?

294
00:18:21,318 --> 00:18:26,020
The home of Barbara Lamar,
the girl who's too beautiful.

295
00:18:26,900 --> 00:18:28,600
That's just a joke, sweetie.

296
00:18:28,600 --> 00:18:31,776
Can't be too beautiful, just
like you can't be too rich.

297
00:18:31,776 --> 00:18:33,270
(chuckles)

298
00:18:33,270 --> 00:18:35,550
Don't squint, darling.

299
00:18:35,550 --> 00:18:38,778
You'll make yourself wear
glasses and that'll be the end.

300
00:18:38,778 --> 00:18:40,290
- Look, there's a castle!

301
00:18:40,290 --> 00:18:42,880
- That's where Jean Harlow used to live.

302
00:18:42,880 --> 00:18:44,970
Jean, our Jean.

303
00:18:44,970 --> 00:18:47,010
The one you were named after.

304
00:18:47,010 --> 00:18:49,460
Look, look, look, over there.

305
00:18:49,460 --> 00:18:50,293
Merna Loy.

306
00:18:51,912 --> 00:18:54,260
(sighs)

307
00:18:54,260 --> 00:18:55,760
Ah,

308
00:18:55,760 --> 00:18:57,530
this is the most famous of all.

309
00:18:59,990 --> 00:19:04,750
Falcon's Lair, home of the
late Rudolph Valentino.

310
00:19:04,750 --> 00:19:07,500
The man had no talent for acting at all.

311
00:19:08,451 --> 00:19:09,401
No talent for life.

312
00:19:11,120 --> 00:19:14,810
But he was photogenic and
he died at the right time.

313
00:19:16,390 --> 00:19:19,390
Remember, Norma Jeane,
die at the right time.

314
00:19:28,852 --> 00:19:33,852
(simple piano music)
(humming)

315
00:19:40,493 --> 00:19:41,743
- That tickles.

316
00:19:43,572 --> 00:19:48,572
- Now don't be silly, you come
back here, finish the piece.

317
00:19:49,249 --> 00:19:51,833
Now.

318
00:19:51,833 --> 00:19:56,833
(humming)
(simple piano music)

319
00:19:57,181 --> 00:19:58,249
(laughing)

320
00:19:58,249 --> 00:20:01,249
- [Gladys] What's going on in there?

321
00:20:04,580 --> 00:20:08,929
- No more lessons today.

322
00:20:08,929 --> 00:20:13,318
(light jazz music)
(laughing)

323
00:20:13,318 --> 00:20:14,318
- Tickle me.

324
00:20:15,699 --> 00:20:17,073
- No.

325
00:20:17,073 --> 00:20:17,941
No.

326
00:20:17,941 --> 00:20:18,937
- Tickle me with your tongue.

327
00:20:19,960 --> 00:20:21,510
- Norma Jeane, behave yourself.

328
00:20:23,218 --> 00:20:24,051
(blows)

329
00:20:24,051 --> 00:20:25,501
Stop that, that's disgusting.

330
00:20:27,250 --> 00:20:29,070
Norma, Clive, what is this?

331
00:20:30,049 --> 00:20:31,100
(blows)

332
00:20:31,100 --> 00:20:31,933
- Not a thing.

333
00:20:34,200 --> 00:20:35,050
What do you mean?

334
00:20:36,650 --> 00:20:38,390
- Norma Jeane, you are all nerved up.

335
00:20:38,390 --> 00:20:39,990
You go into your room right now.

336
00:20:43,381 --> 00:20:44,214
(laughs)

337
00:20:44,214 --> 00:20:45,860
Naughty, giggling little girl.

338
00:20:46,950 --> 00:20:49,300
- My mother called Los
Angeles the city of sin.

339
00:20:50,610 --> 00:20:53,237
She said mankind wasn't
meant to live here,

340
00:20:53,237 --> 00:20:57,340
that we were being punished for
our stupidity and our pride.

341
00:20:57,340 --> 00:20:59,750
- Norma Jeane, there's fire in the hills.

342
00:21:00,700 --> 00:21:01,533
20 feet high.

343
00:21:02,463 --> 00:21:03,740
Fields of fire.

344
00:21:05,060 --> 00:21:06,080
Canyons of fire.

345
00:21:07,021 --> 00:21:08,390
I heard it on the radio.

346
00:21:09,420 --> 00:21:10,830
Hurry, come on.

347
00:21:10,830 --> 00:21:13,353
We'll go to your father's,
we'll be safe there.

348
00:21:13,353 --> 00:21:14,186
- Where?

349
00:21:14,186 --> 00:21:17,500
- Earthquakes, fires,
the air smothering us.

350
00:21:19,330 --> 00:21:24,330
Some of us were born here,
and some of us would die here.

351
00:21:25,290 --> 00:21:27,838
It's a pact we made with the devil.

352
00:21:27,838 --> 00:21:30,588
(sirens wailing)

353
00:21:37,554 --> 00:21:42,554
(whistle blowing)
(men chattering)

354
00:21:44,100 --> 00:21:45,680
- Where the hell do
you think you're going?

355
00:21:45,680 --> 00:21:47,110
- I wanna see hell close up.

356
00:21:48,153 --> 00:21:50,070
- Who's that with you?

357
00:21:50,070 --> 00:21:52,130
- Well, that's Shirley Temple.

358
00:21:52,130 --> 00:21:54,690
Look, I had been invited
to a private residence

359
00:21:54,690 --> 00:21:56,450
at the top of Little Canyon.

360
00:21:56,450 --> 00:21:59,020
The owner has a fireproof mansion,

361
00:21:59,020 --> 00:22:02,090
I can't say the man's name,
but it's one that you all know.

362
00:22:02,090 --> 00:22:05,620
He's in the film industry,
and this is his daughter.

363
00:22:05,620 --> 00:22:08,900
- Well, I'm sorry ma'am,
you can't go up this road.

364
00:22:08,900 --> 00:22:11,050
Why don't you go home, calm down,

365
00:22:11,050 --> 00:22:12,930
and put your little girl to bed.

366
00:22:12,930 --> 00:22:14,660
- Don't you condescend to me, Officer,

367
00:22:14,660 --> 00:22:16,500
don't you tell me what to do.

368
00:22:16,500 --> 00:22:18,750
- Lady, you're either drunk or doped up,

369
00:22:18,750 --> 00:22:21,100
and nobody's got time for it tonight.

370
00:22:21,100 --> 00:22:23,530
- Why don't you just shoot me.

371
00:22:27,152 --> 00:22:29,985
(tires squealing)

372
00:22:36,659 --> 00:22:37,855
- Was he here?

373
00:22:37,855 --> 00:22:39,059
Father?

374
00:22:39,059 --> 00:22:40,831
All this time?

375
00:22:40,831 --> 00:22:41,980
Why didn't he come and see us?

376
00:22:41,980 --> 00:22:45,895
- You shut up!

377
00:22:45,895 --> 00:22:47,900
It isn't fair.

378
00:22:49,340 --> 00:22:50,710
I'm 34 years old.

379
00:22:51,880 --> 00:22:53,970
No man'll look at me anymore.

380
00:22:54,880 --> 00:22:57,610
I've given my youth to the
studio for what, for you!

381
00:22:59,522 --> 00:23:02,030
(knocking)

382
00:23:02,030 --> 00:23:02,863
- Norma Jeane.

383
00:23:04,530 --> 00:23:07,970
- Mother called the studio
to tell them she was sick.

384
00:23:07,970 --> 00:23:10,840
They were mean, they told
her not to come back to work.

385
00:23:12,977 --> 00:23:14,440
- Unlock the door.

386
00:23:15,580 --> 00:23:17,680
- [Norma Jeane] I can't, Mr. Pierce.

387
00:23:17,680 --> 00:23:19,140
She made me promise.

388
00:23:21,690 --> 00:23:23,390
- How long have you been in there?

389
00:23:24,407 --> 00:23:25,640
- Two days.

390
00:23:28,953 --> 00:23:31,210
- I brought you some food.

391
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:34,130
I'll leave it right outside the door.

392
00:23:43,400 --> 00:23:44,233
- Poison.

393
00:23:45,150 --> 00:23:46,977
They're trying to poison me.

394
00:23:46,977 --> 00:23:47,955
(plate clatters)

395
00:23:47,955 --> 00:23:50,155
- No Mother, it was
your friend, Mr. Pierce.

396
00:23:51,240 --> 00:23:56,000
- Your father gave me
$225 to get rid of you

397
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:57,350
before you were even born.

398
00:23:58,740 --> 00:24:00,190
I should've listened to him.

399
00:24:01,490 --> 00:24:03,420
He loved me before I got pregnant,

400
00:24:03,420 --> 00:24:06,280
then after, don't call me,
don't follow me on the street.

401
00:24:11,560 --> 00:24:13,020
I have to cleanse you.

402
00:24:14,640 --> 00:24:16,559
- [Norma Jeane] No Mother, please!

403
00:24:16,559 --> 00:24:17,900
- [Gladys] You're afflicted.

404
00:24:17,900 --> 00:24:19,300
I have to make you clean.

405
00:24:19,300 --> 00:24:20,133
- Mother!

406
00:24:20,133 --> 00:24:21,070
- I have to.

407
00:24:22,520 --> 00:24:24,110
I have to.

408
00:24:24,110 --> 00:24:24,943
You're a freak.

409
00:24:25,995 --> 00:24:29,240
A freak with deformity
disguised as a little girl.

410
00:24:30,375 --> 00:24:32,458
(crying)

411
00:24:33,840 --> 00:24:35,470
It's you.

412
00:24:35,470 --> 00:24:38,191
You're the reason your father went away!

413
00:24:38,191 --> 00:24:39,430
He didn't want you!

414
00:24:39,430 --> 00:24:40,263
- Mr. Pierce!

415
00:24:41,490 --> 00:24:42,343
(knocking)

416
00:24:42,343 --> 00:24:43,260
Mr. Pierce!

417
00:24:44,219 --> 00:24:47,579
(bell ringing)

418
00:24:47,579 --> 00:24:52,579
(somber music)
(people chattering)

419
00:24:58,525 --> 00:25:00,716
- [Man] Open up in there, come on!

420
00:25:00,716 --> 00:25:03,012
(banging on door)

421
00:25:03,012 --> 00:25:03,869
- Go away!

422
00:25:03,869 --> 00:25:05,119
Leave me alone!

423
00:25:12,708 --> 00:25:14,701
- You're coming with us now.

424
00:25:14,701 --> 00:25:15,534
- Stop it!

425
00:25:15,534 --> 00:25:17,986
(fire roaring)

426
00:25:17,986 --> 00:25:20,236
(shouting)

427
00:25:29,450 --> 00:25:31,033
There's three more.

428
00:25:35,345 --> 00:25:37,928
(somber music)

429
00:25:40,986 --> 00:25:43,819
(car door closes)

430
00:25:47,985 --> 00:25:49,818
- Please, Norma Jeane.

431
00:25:51,045 --> 00:25:53,194
- You said you were taking
me to see my mother.

432
00:25:53,194 --> 00:25:55,326
- Please, Norma Jeane, be a good girl.

433
00:25:55,326 --> 00:25:56,655
- This is an orphanage!

434
00:25:56,655 --> 00:25:58,100
- Don't kick people, Norma Jeane.

435
00:26:00,009 --> 00:26:01,850
There's nowhere else I can take you.

436
00:26:01,850 --> 00:26:03,130
Your mother is sick.

437
00:26:03,130 --> 00:26:06,240
The doctors say she's very sick.

438
00:26:06,240 --> 00:26:07,840
She tried to hurt you, she can't be

439
00:26:07,840 --> 00:26:09,420
a mother to you right now.

440
00:26:10,520 --> 00:26:12,230
Forgive me, Norma Jeane.

441
00:26:12,230 --> 00:26:13,080
Ow!

442
00:26:13,080 --> 00:26:13,913
Norma Jeane!

443
00:26:15,930 --> 00:26:17,190
Bad girl, very bad.

444
00:26:22,799 --> 00:26:25,680
Don't you understand, I feel terrible,

445
00:26:25,680 --> 00:26:27,030
but I can't be your mother.

446
00:26:28,491 --> 00:26:31,270
God knows, I have to work,
I have no money saved.

447
00:26:40,938 --> 00:26:42,282
- This is a mistake.

448
00:26:42,282 --> 00:26:43,240
I have a mother.

449
00:26:43,240 --> 00:26:45,420
I have a father.

450
00:26:45,420 --> 00:26:47,770
He lives in a big
mansion in Beverly Hills.

451
00:26:47,770 --> 00:26:50,960
- Child, save your
tears, you may need them.

452
00:26:53,750 --> 00:26:57,130
- There was a fairy tale I
used to tell Norma Jeane.

453
00:26:57,130 --> 00:26:58,400
I made it up myself.

454
00:26:59,660 --> 00:27:01,030
Little girl who sees too much,

455
00:27:01,030 --> 00:27:03,840
little girl who hears too much.

456
00:27:05,550 --> 00:27:09,900
A crow comes to peck out her eyes,

457
00:27:09,900 --> 00:27:12,750
a big fish comes to gobble up her ears,

458
00:27:12,750 --> 00:27:15,820
a red fox bites off her nose.

459
00:27:18,790 --> 00:27:22,586
See what happens, Miss?

460
00:27:22,586 --> 00:27:25,336
(girls shouting)

461
00:27:32,273 --> 00:27:34,273
(gasps)

462
00:27:41,740 --> 00:27:42,740
- Smells like smoke.

463
00:27:43,720 --> 00:27:44,553
What happened?

464
00:27:45,520 --> 00:27:47,140
Where do you wear these?

465
00:27:47,140 --> 00:27:48,718
Movie star clothes.

466
00:27:48,718 --> 00:27:51,468
(girls laughing)

467
00:27:52,522 --> 00:27:53,822
Look at me, Ginger Rogers.

468
00:27:54,802 --> 00:27:57,552
(girls laughing)

469
00:28:01,453 --> 00:28:04,910
Why you holding that freaky thing?

470
00:28:04,910 --> 00:28:05,743
A little mouse.

471
00:28:06,820 --> 00:28:08,620
Cat got your tongue?

472
00:28:08,620 --> 00:28:10,080
Little orphan girl?

473
00:28:10,080 --> 00:28:11,990
- I'm not an orphan.

474
00:28:11,990 --> 00:28:13,880
My mother's in the hospital.

475
00:28:13,880 --> 00:28:17,413
My father lives in a big
mansion in Beverly Hills.

476
00:28:17,413 --> 00:28:18,660
- That's bull.

477
00:28:18,660 --> 00:28:20,114
Liar.
(bell ringing)

478
00:28:20,114 --> 00:28:22,710
Your mother and father are
dead, just like everybody else.

479
00:28:22,710 --> 00:28:23,660
Everybody's dead.

480
00:28:30,193 --> 00:28:35,193
(somber music)
(insects chirping)

481
00:28:48,280 --> 00:28:49,760
- [Man] And Clara and her prince

482
00:28:49,760 --> 00:28:51,880
sailed home in a magic sleigh.

483
00:28:51,880 --> 00:28:54,460
- And they lived happily ever after.

484
00:28:54,460 --> 00:28:55,524
The end.

485
00:28:55,524 --> 00:28:59,024
(cheering and applauding)

486
00:29:00,183 --> 00:29:01,840
Merry Christmas, dear children.

487
00:29:01,840 --> 00:29:03,595
Now we have presents for everybody!

488
00:29:03,595 --> 00:29:05,408
(girls shouting)

489
00:29:05,408 --> 00:29:06,548
- [Man] This is yours.

490
00:29:06,548 --> 00:29:07,381
Here you go.

491
00:29:07,381 --> 00:29:09,399
- And this one's for you.

492
00:29:09,399 --> 00:29:13,208
- A fairy princess and a dark prince.

493
00:29:13,208 --> 00:29:14,395
- What?

494
00:29:14,395 --> 00:29:15,504
- Don't you know?

495
00:29:15,504 --> 00:29:19,680
Movie stars.

496
00:29:19,680 --> 00:29:20,630
- Come on up stage.

497
00:29:21,625 --> 00:29:22,458
Oh come on, you'll be all right.

498
00:29:25,120 --> 00:29:26,140
- Hi.

499
00:29:26,140 --> 00:29:26,973
- [Photographer] There you
go, that's a great one.

500
00:29:27,924 --> 00:29:28,757
I gotta get one.

501
00:29:28,757 --> 00:29:29,932
- Come on honey, a nice smile.

502
00:29:29,932 --> 00:29:30,860
- [Photographer] Give us a big smile.

503
00:29:30,860 --> 00:29:33,010
Come on sweetie, let's see it.

504
00:29:34,304 --> 00:29:37,020
Oh, look at that, beautiful.

505
00:29:37,020 --> 00:29:38,070
All right, hold that.

506
00:29:40,429 --> 00:29:41,870
- Open your present, darling.

507
00:29:43,641 --> 00:29:45,070
What is that?

508
00:29:45,070 --> 00:29:46,940
- A baby tiger, mine.

509
00:29:55,075 --> 00:29:56,825
Where are you, Daddy?

510
00:29:58,036 --> 00:30:00,200
If I was prettier, would you come for me?

511
00:30:02,011 --> 00:30:04,120
(somber music)

512
00:30:04,120 --> 00:30:08,130
Someone come to take me away,
so I'll never be sad again.

513
00:30:20,510 --> 00:30:21,343
You.

514
00:30:22,550 --> 00:30:24,320
You could be my magic friend.

515
00:30:29,131 --> 00:30:32,048
(girls chattering)

516
00:30:39,224 --> 00:30:42,010
- You're a very hard worker, Norma Jeane.

517
00:30:42,010 --> 00:30:45,060
You must know that cleanliness
is next to godliness.

518
00:30:45,060 --> 00:30:48,523
- My mother doesn't believe in God.

519
00:30:48,523 --> 00:30:52,510
- Perhaps your mother's
mind has been poisoned.

520
00:30:53,815 --> 00:30:56,330
I believe that a person can surmount

521
00:30:56,330 --> 00:30:59,240
any of life's challenges
through hard work and prayer.

522
00:31:00,520 --> 00:31:02,830
Without drugs, without alcohol.

523
00:31:02,830 --> 00:31:04,692
- I will never take drugs.

524
00:31:04,692 --> 00:31:06,090
I will never, ever drink.

525
00:31:07,499 --> 00:31:09,890
- I have some books you
might find interesting.

526
00:31:11,018 --> 00:31:13,118
You have an inquisitive mind, Norma Jeane.

527
00:31:13,960 --> 00:31:14,793
Put it to use.

528
00:31:21,404 --> 00:31:23,987
(bell ringing)

529
00:31:30,210 --> 00:31:32,100
- [Woman] She looks just
like our Cynthia Rose.

530
00:31:32,970 --> 00:31:35,552
- Mr. And Mrs. Mount lost
their little daughter

531
00:31:35,552 --> 00:31:36,980
when she was eight years old.

532
00:31:36,980 --> 00:31:38,362
- Polio.

533
00:31:38,362 --> 00:31:39,550
We have a picture.

534
00:31:46,930 --> 00:31:47,900
- [Norma Jeane] Pretty.

535
00:31:47,900 --> 00:31:50,090
- Norma Jeane, why don't you recite

536
00:31:50,090 --> 00:31:52,090
one of your poems for these nice people?

537
00:31:53,050 --> 00:31:54,590
Norma Jeane's become quite a poet

538
00:31:54,590 --> 00:31:56,910
while she's been staying with us.

539
00:31:56,910 --> 00:31:58,070
- Poet.

540
00:31:58,070 --> 00:31:59,710
On top of everything else.

541
00:31:59,710 --> 00:32:01,010
Oh yes, we'd love to hear.

542
00:32:03,390 --> 00:32:05,960
- Where do you go when you disappear?

543
00:32:05,960 --> 00:32:08,650
Wherever you are, are you alone?

544
00:32:08,650 --> 00:32:12,790
You can endure any pain, if
you have a family and a home.

545
00:32:15,960 --> 00:32:18,050
- Darling, we have a home for you.

546
00:32:18,050 --> 00:32:20,390
A beautiful home in Pasadena.

547
00:32:20,390 --> 00:32:22,120
There's a room just for you.

548
00:32:22,120 --> 00:32:24,510
It's pale pink and there's
a canopy over the bed.

549
00:32:24,510 --> 00:32:29,160
- Norma Jeane, would you
like to live with us?

550
00:32:29,160 --> 00:32:30,850
- Yes, can I be Cynthia Rose?

551
00:32:35,426 --> 00:32:38,176
(birds chirping)

552
00:32:39,279 --> 00:32:41,362
- I'm sorry, Norma Jeane.

553
00:32:42,520 --> 00:32:44,710
I know your mother loves you, dear,

554
00:32:44,710 --> 00:32:46,010
and wants you to be happy.

555
00:32:47,498 --> 00:32:51,890
But she refuses to sign
the adoption papers again.

556
00:32:52,851 --> 00:32:54,620
- It isn't fair, Dr. Mittelstadt.

557
00:32:55,560 --> 00:32:57,980
My mother, she's sick and she's crazy.

558
00:32:57,980 --> 00:32:59,170
- Norma Jeane.

559
00:32:59,170 --> 00:33:02,940
- This is the third time I had
a chance to be in a family.

560
00:33:02,940 --> 00:33:05,050
I did everything you said.

561
00:33:05,050 --> 00:33:08,100
I wrote to my mother, I begged her,

562
00:33:08,100 --> 00:33:09,770
I prayed and prayed and prayed.

563
00:33:09,770 --> 00:33:12,680
- Prayer cannot change
the science of being.

564
00:33:12,680 --> 00:33:15,830
It only brings us in
better harmony with it.

565
00:33:15,830 --> 00:33:17,130
- Then what good is it?

566
00:33:18,220 --> 00:33:21,030
- My mother didn't know
how to be a mother to me.

567
00:33:22,901 --> 00:33:26,330
But she didn't want anyone
else to be my mother,

568
00:33:26,330 --> 00:33:30,650
so Dr. Mittelstadt promised
to find me a foster home.

569
00:33:32,490 --> 00:33:34,760
We didn't need my mother's
permission for that.

570
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:40,290
A foster home, didn't make any difference.

571
00:33:40,290 --> 00:33:45,290
Any home, any home at all.

572
00:33:45,930 --> 00:33:49,250
Well, Norma Jeane, we will miss you.

573
00:33:50,500 --> 00:33:52,790
- Yes, I will miss all of you.

574
00:33:52,790 --> 00:33:54,690
- The Perigs are a good foster family.

575
00:33:55,595 --> 00:33:57,980
You'll be going to school in Van Ives.

576
00:33:57,980 --> 00:34:00,350
And if things work out
well, you'll be able

577
00:34:00,350 --> 00:34:02,050
to live with them until you're 18.

578
00:34:02,890 --> 00:34:04,090
Then you're on your own.

579
00:34:05,460 --> 00:34:08,352
Now, there's $20.60 in your account.

580
00:34:08,352 --> 00:34:13,299
As a going away gift,
I've doubled that sum.

581
00:34:13,299 --> 00:34:15,980
- Thank you.

582
00:34:15,980 --> 00:34:18,390
- Remember us with kindness, Norma Jeane.

583
00:34:26,523 --> 00:34:29,273
(birds chirping)

584
00:34:36,932 --> 00:34:41,932
(upbeat jazz music)
(door opens)

585
00:34:48,862 --> 00:34:50,710
- Oh, Norma Jeane, let
me take that from you.

586
00:34:50,710 --> 00:34:52,237
- Oh--

587
00:34:52,237 --> 00:34:54,560
- No, honey, honey, you do
enough around here already.

588
00:34:54,560 --> 00:34:55,510
Doesn't she Warren?

589
00:34:56,372 --> 00:34:57,220
- Yeah.

590
00:34:57,220 --> 00:34:59,980
- Yeah, you always keep
your room so neat and tidy,

591
00:34:59,980 --> 00:35:01,210
and look at you, you always look like

592
00:35:01,210 --> 00:35:02,945
you just stepped out of the bathtub.

593
00:35:02,945 --> 00:35:04,088
(Norma Jeane laughs)

594
00:35:04,088 --> 00:35:06,490
Here, why don't you have a seat
and let me fix you a plate.

595
00:35:16,640 --> 00:35:18,330
This is a big day for you.

596
00:35:18,330 --> 00:35:20,730
- You don't have to
wait on me, Aunt Elsie.

597
00:35:20,730 --> 00:35:22,250
- Did you memorize your play?

598
00:35:22,250 --> 00:35:24,750
- Yeah, I worked on it
practically all night,

599
00:35:24,750 --> 00:35:28,090
I'm so nervous, Aunt
Elsie, my head, my stomach.

600
00:35:30,481 --> 00:35:31,610
- Do you need an aspirin?

601
00:35:31,610 --> 00:35:35,660
- No, I'll be fine, I just
gotta set my mind to it.

602
00:35:36,602 --> 00:35:38,300
- You always say that.

603
00:35:38,300 --> 00:35:39,450
It doesn't work for me.

604
00:35:40,550 --> 00:35:42,752
Maybe it's because I
only have half a mind.

605
00:35:42,752 --> 00:35:45,419
(both laughing)

606
00:35:47,002 --> 00:35:48,585
- What's in a name?

607
00:35:49,756 --> 00:35:51,650
That which we call a
rose by any other name

608
00:35:51,650 --> 00:35:52,700
would smell as sweet.

609
00:35:54,110 --> 00:35:56,640
So Romeo would, were he not Romeo called,

610
00:35:57,660 --> 00:36:00,196
retain that dear perfection which he owes

611
00:36:00,196 --> 00:36:02,680
without that title.

612
00:36:02,680 --> 00:36:05,880
Romeo, doth thy name and for thy name,

613
00:36:07,050 --> 00:36:09,570
which is no part of thee, take all myself.

614
00:36:12,565 --> 00:36:14,836
(sighs)

615
00:36:14,836 --> 00:36:17,170
Thank you, magic friend.

616
00:36:17,170 --> 00:36:18,380
Thank you.

617
00:36:18,380 --> 00:36:19,630
- Next.

618
00:36:19,630 --> 00:36:20,470
Who's next?

619
00:36:21,900 --> 00:36:25,130
(whispering)

620
00:36:25,130 --> 00:36:26,020
Norma Jeane.

621
00:36:47,140 --> 00:36:48,340
- What's in a name?

622
00:36:49,850 --> 00:36:51,870
A name by any other rose...

623
00:36:54,200 --> 00:36:59,200
A rose by any other name
would smell as sweet,

624
00:36:59,330 --> 00:37:00,940
so to...

625
00:37:02,710 --> 00:37:04,270
I'm sorry, could I start again?

626
00:37:06,460 --> 00:37:11,460
No, see, I think I could be
Juliet, I know, I am Juliet.

627
00:37:12,176 --> 00:37:15,340
(students laughing)

628
00:37:15,340 --> 00:37:20,340
- Thank you, Norma Jeane, but
I don't think the playwright

629
00:37:20,460 --> 00:37:24,198
Mr. William Shakespeare
would've seen it that way.

630
00:37:24,198 --> 00:37:27,198
(students laughing)

631
00:37:28,852 --> 00:37:29,685
(crying)

632
00:37:29,685 --> 00:37:32,132
- This all may seem important
to you now, Norma Jeane.

633
00:37:32,132 --> 00:37:36,460
Someday you'll laugh about it.

634
00:37:36,460 --> 00:37:39,370
- I couldn't even make
it as a cheerleader.

635
00:37:39,370 --> 00:37:41,870
- That's because you're a
poet, not a cheerleader.

636
00:37:44,151 --> 00:37:45,670
- Do you mean that, Mr. Herring?

637
00:37:47,520 --> 00:37:48,630
- I've read your poems.

638
00:37:50,546 --> 00:37:51,600
They're very good.

639
00:37:52,790 --> 00:37:53,900
Good rhyming.

640
00:37:53,900 --> 00:37:57,040
- I have lots of them, hundreds
of them, I love poetry.

641
00:37:58,462 --> 00:37:59,782
- Well bring them in.

642
00:37:59,782 --> 00:38:00,910
I'm happy to read them.

643
00:38:02,060 --> 00:38:05,720
- I wanna write poetry like
Edna St. Vincent Millay,

644
00:38:06,720 --> 00:38:07,720
or Robert Browning.

645
00:38:08,900 --> 00:38:10,600
Oh, Mr. Herring, I wanna learn.

646
00:38:18,987 --> 00:38:22,946
And my mother, she was a
film actress for the studio,

647
00:38:22,946 --> 00:38:26,050
she was an understudy for Joan
Crawford and Gloria Swanson.

648
00:38:27,100 --> 00:38:29,800
Well she died in an airplane
crash over the Atlantic

649
00:38:29,800 --> 00:38:34,800
in 1934, and there was no
one to take me in, so--

650
00:38:35,250 --> 00:38:37,550
- Life must be very
difficult for a young girl

651
00:38:38,546 --> 00:38:40,610
like yourself, Norma Jeane.

652
00:38:40,610 --> 00:38:43,180
- I love the way you say my name.

653
00:38:43,180 --> 00:38:46,561
It makes me feel magical.

654
00:38:46,561 --> 00:38:50,190
You can kiss me, but only
with your mouth closed.

655
00:38:55,320 --> 00:38:58,290
Thank you, Mr. Herring, you're
the most wonderful teacher

656
00:38:58,290 --> 00:38:59,680
in the whole wide world.

657
00:39:08,739 --> 00:39:10,075
(light music)

658
00:39:10,075 --> 00:39:12,909
(insects chirping)

659
00:39:12,909 --> 00:39:13,826
This is me.

660
00:39:18,772 --> 00:39:20,210
Well, just a little kiss.

661
00:39:21,849 --> 00:39:24,567
Not the kind with your mouth open.

662
00:39:30,661 --> 00:39:32,990
Bye.

663
00:39:44,455 --> 00:39:46,850
- What is it, Warren?

664
00:39:46,850 --> 00:39:47,870
- Nothing.

665
00:39:47,870 --> 00:39:50,040
- Norma Jeane wasn't the
one to blame for this.

666
00:39:51,770 --> 00:39:53,370
My husband was the one to blame.

667
00:39:55,140 --> 00:39:57,540
And even that poor bastard
was halfway innocent.

668
00:39:59,100 --> 00:40:00,100
Maybe even helpless.

669
00:40:02,890 --> 00:40:03,810
Have to face it.

670
00:40:05,140 --> 00:40:06,190
It's a man's world.

671
00:40:07,520 --> 00:40:12,060
And to survive, a woman
must betray her own kind.

672
00:40:15,475 --> 00:40:16,580
A woman has to protect herself

673
00:40:16,580 --> 00:40:18,180
against a girl like Norma Jeane.

674
00:40:24,705 --> 00:40:25,538
(birds chirping)

675
00:40:25,538 --> 00:40:27,310
Norma Jeane, I been
thinking about something.

676
00:40:29,400 --> 00:40:31,630
It's time that you got married.

677
00:40:31,630 --> 00:40:32,860
- What?

678
00:40:32,860 --> 00:40:35,439
- Well you know, you're
gonna be 16 in June.

679
00:40:35,439 --> 00:40:37,630
And that's about the time I got married.

680
00:40:38,840 --> 00:40:40,740
- But I don't have a steady boyfriend.

681
00:40:42,100 --> 00:40:43,650
- You have too many boyfriends.

682
00:40:44,540 --> 00:40:46,120
- But I'm not in love.

683
00:40:46,120 --> 00:40:47,950
- At your age it's easy to get in love.

684
00:40:49,510 --> 00:40:53,533
And say, Norma Jeane, I've been hearing

685
00:40:53,533 --> 00:40:56,280
some things about you lately.

686
00:40:56,280 --> 00:40:58,080
- Oh, you mean Mr. Herring, my teacher?

687
00:40:58,080 --> 00:40:59,620
I'm not seeing him anymore, Aunt Elsie,

688
00:40:59,620 --> 00:41:02,150
I didn't know he was married, I swear.

689
00:41:02,150 --> 00:41:03,640
- With this terrible war starting

690
00:41:03,640 --> 00:41:06,500
and all of our young
boys going off to fight,

691
00:41:06,500 --> 00:41:07,940
you better grab yourself a husband

692
00:41:07,940 --> 00:41:10,410
while there's still one
available and in one piece.

693
00:41:11,828 --> 00:41:14,200
(lighter clicking)

694
00:41:14,200 --> 00:41:17,560
- You're serious, you're not joking?

695
00:41:17,560 --> 00:41:19,750
- Do I look like I'm joking?

696
00:41:19,750 --> 00:41:20,583
Does Hitler?

697
00:41:22,823 --> 00:41:25,950
- But I still have two
years of high school to go.

698
00:41:26,900 --> 00:41:29,590
- Honey, you don't need
a diploma to get married.

699
00:41:29,590 --> 00:41:32,100
- But I'm too young, Aunt Elsie.

700
00:41:32,100 --> 00:41:33,250
I don't wanna get married.

701
00:41:33,250 --> 00:41:35,170
I wanna be a nurse, with the war going on

702
00:41:35,170 --> 00:41:36,210
I can help all the suffering--

703
00:41:36,210 --> 00:41:37,360
- We don't have the room anymore,

704
00:41:37,360 --> 00:41:39,030
my sister and her kids
are gonna come here--

705
00:41:39,030 --> 00:41:40,640
- I don't need an actual room, I mean,

706
00:41:40,640 --> 00:41:43,000
I could sleep on the sofa, or in the car.

707
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:45,880
Aunt Elsie, I'll do anything,
I'll work harder Aunt Elsie--

708
00:41:45,880 --> 00:41:47,270
- Honey, you do work hard.

709
00:41:47,270 --> 00:41:49,070
- Please don't send me back
to the home, Aunt Elsie,

710
00:41:49,070 --> 00:41:51,110
I'll kill myself, I will.

711
00:41:51,110 --> 00:41:52,184
- Stop it.

712
00:41:52,184 --> 00:41:53,940
(Norma Jeane crying)

713
00:41:53,940 --> 00:41:54,990
Crying never helps.

714
00:41:57,967 --> 00:41:59,920
If it did, we'd all be a
lot better off, wouldn't we?

715
00:42:01,030 --> 00:42:03,070
- Why do you want to get rid of her?

716
00:42:03,070 --> 00:42:04,920
She helps you around
the house, doesn't she?

717
00:42:04,920 --> 00:42:05,753
- Mm-hmm.

718
00:42:07,440 --> 00:42:08,390
- She's a good kid.

719
00:42:09,519 --> 00:42:12,169
- Well we certainly don't
her to end up like Lucille.

720
00:42:13,500 --> 00:42:17,680
15, pregnant, that boy
just ran out on her.

721
00:42:17,680 --> 00:42:20,820
- So what, you're just gonna
send her back to County?

722
00:42:20,820 --> 00:42:21,920
Back to the orphanage?

723
00:42:22,970 --> 00:42:23,803
- No.

724
00:42:24,895 --> 00:42:27,640
I'm gonna get that little girl
married, outta here and safe.

725
00:42:32,471 --> 00:42:33,304
Ba ba.

726
00:42:33,304 --> 00:42:37,930
- I'm sorry, Aunt Elsie,
I'm just scared I guess.

727
00:42:37,930 --> 00:42:39,610
- Oh, I understand, honey.

728
00:42:39,610 --> 00:42:41,320
But you'll get over it.

729
00:42:41,320 --> 00:42:43,751
Wait till you see this boy.

730
00:42:43,751 --> 00:42:45,430
He's so cute.

731
00:42:45,430 --> 00:42:46,330
And a hard worker.

732
00:42:47,360 --> 00:42:49,590
He works at Lockheed now,
but I think after the war

733
00:42:49,590 --> 00:42:51,731
he'll probably have his own business.

734
00:42:51,731 --> 00:42:55,880
- I wish I could go to the
war, I wish I was a man.

735
00:42:55,880 --> 00:42:57,447
- You?

736
00:42:57,447 --> 00:42:59,187
You can't even watch me clean a chicken.

737
00:42:59,187 --> 00:43:01,550
(laughs)

738
00:43:01,550 --> 00:43:02,450
Oh, this war.

739
00:43:03,710 --> 00:43:06,300
It is getting so bad in Europe.

740
00:43:06,300 --> 00:43:10,180
All the young boys have enlisted now.

741
00:43:10,180 --> 00:43:13,190
You wanna have babies, don't you?

742
00:43:13,190 --> 00:43:14,200
- Babies?

743
00:43:14,200 --> 00:43:16,120
- Time's running out.

744
00:43:16,120 --> 00:43:20,835
- Well, if I had a baby, I
would never be alone, would I?

745
00:43:20,835 --> 00:43:22,235
- That's right, Norma Jeane.

746
00:43:23,170 --> 00:43:25,090
You'd never be alone.

747
00:43:26,060 --> 00:43:27,680
This is for your own good, baby.

748
00:43:27,680 --> 00:43:29,834
You have to grow up sometime.

749
00:43:29,834 --> 00:43:32,880
I guess if your number's
up, Aunt Elsie, it's up.

750
00:43:33,910 --> 00:43:35,290
- Yeah.

751
00:43:35,290 --> 00:43:37,010
- She's a good Christian
girl and she doesn't

752
00:43:37,010 --> 00:43:37,843
drink or smoke.

753
00:43:38,700 --> 00:43:41,520
She reads the Bible, and
she's a born homemaker.

754
00:43:43,760 --> 00:43:45,120
You have to go overseas, you're gonna need

755
00:43:45,120 --> 00:43:46,420
someone to come home to.

756
00:43:47,750 --> 00:43:49,100
- Mom.

757
00:43:49,100 --> 00:43:51,060
Got you to come home to, right?

758
00:43:51,060 --> 00:43:52,420
And write to me?

759
00:43:52,420 --> 00:43:54,840
Why would I need anybody else?

760
00:43:54,840 --> 00:43:57,020
- Now Bucky, you just promise me.

761
00:43:58,660 --> 00:43:59,610
Just be nice.

762
00:44:01,296 --> 00:44:03,170
- Okay.

763
00:44:05,185 --> 00:44:06,770
- Hi Bess, how are you?

764
00:44:06,770 --> 00:44:08,100
Good, good to see you.

765
00:44:09,675 --> 00:44:14,675
Go ahead.

766
00:44:21,060 --> 00:44:22,610
- Hi.

767
00:44:22,610 --> 00:44:23,443
I'm Bucky.

768
00:44:25,140 --> 00:44:26,880
- I'm Norma Jeane.

769
00:44:27,859 --> 00:44:31,640
- Well, Norma Jeane,
you're the prettiest girl

770
00:44:31,640 --> 00:44:33,319
I've seen outside the movies.

771
00:44:33,319 --> 00:44:34,830
(laughs)

772
00:44:34,830 --> 00:44:37,230
I'm beginning to believe
in love at first sight.

773
00:44:39,629 --> 00:44:41,267
(Norma Jeane laughs)

774
00:44:41,267 --> 00:44:43,451
(soft jazz music)

775
00:44:43,451 --> 00:44:46,451
(people chattering)

776
00:45:04,564 --> 00:45:06,814
(laughing)

777
00:45:07,798 --> 00:45:09,420
- What did your family say when they saw

778
00:45:09,420 --> 00:45:11,670
my birth certificate, father unknown?

779
00:45:11,670 --> 00:45:14,460
- Don't give it another thought, honey.

780
00:45:14,460 --> 00:45:16,070
No Glazer's gonna look down on somebody

781
00:45:16,070 --> 00:45:17,530
for reasons that can't be helped.

782
00:45:17,530 --> 00:45:19,316
I'll punch 'em in the nose if they do.

783
00:45:19,316 --> 00:45:20,516
(laughs)

784
00:45:20,516 --> 00:45:21,450
Thank you.

785
00:45:21,450 --> 00:45:22,630
- Ooh, I think I've had enough,

786
00:45:22,630 --> 00:45:24,270
I've never had champagne before.

787
00:45:25,138 --> 00:45:27,011
- Oh, hey!
(Norma Jean squeals)

788
00:45:27,011 --> 00:45:28,178
- [Man] Sorry.

789
00:45:29,250 --> 00:45:30,452
(Bucky laughing)

790
00:45:30,452 --> 00:45:31,545
Easy.

791
00:45:31,545 --> 00:45:33,462
Look, I said I'm sorry.

792
00:45:39,990 --> 00:45:41,010
- Oh dear.

793
00:45:42,140 --> 00:45:43,890
And Bucky's sister was kind enough

794
00:45:43,890 --> 00:45:45,510
to let you borrow her dress.

795
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:48,912
Just like the movies, huh?

796
00:45:48,912 --> 00:45:51,620
- I just wish my mother
could've been here.

797
00:45:51,620 --> 00:45:53,708
I sent her an invitation, but--

798
00:45:53,708 --> 00:45:55,852
- Well, you never have
to fret about that again.

799
00:45:55,852 --> 00:45:57,324
Now you have a mother-in-law.

800
00:45:57,324 --> 00:45:59,572
(laughs)

801
00:45:59,572 --> 00:46:01,252
- Oh, Aunt Elsie, I'm frightened.

802
00:46:01,252 --> 00:46:03,102
I mean, I'm frightened about tonight.

803
00:46:04,044 --> 00:46:05,320
- Oh honey, don't be frightened.

804
00:46:05,320 --> 00:46:08,708
All you have to do really
is stay outta their way.

805
00:46:08,708 --> 00:46:10,791
(laughs)

806
00:46:12,535 --> 00:46:15,543
I wish I coulda kicked
Warren out and kept you.

807
00:46:27,400 --> 00:46:28,680
