02:21:59,140 --> 02:22:00,890
I always thought I could play Natasha.

2509
02:22:00,890 --> 02:22:03,280
I mean, someone like
me could play Natasha,

2510
02:22:03,280 --> 02:22:06,450
'cause well, she doesn't
belong in a good family,

2511
02:22:06,450 --> 02:22:10,130
and people laugh at her. (laughs)

2512
02:22:10,130 --> 02:22:13,610
See, but then Chekhov, well
he surprises you because

2513
02:22:15,028 --> 02:22:17,930
Natasha, who has her sympathy,

2514
02:22:17,930 --> 02:22:21,627
but she turns out to be so
selfish, so devious, really bad.

2515
02:22:24,660 --> 02:22:27,430
- You're saying I made Magda too good.

2516
02:22:27,430 --> 02:22:28,940
- No.

2517
02:22:28,940 --> 02:22:31,641
I guess, (laughs)

2518
02:22:31,641 --> 02:22:33,451
I guess I said the wrong thing.

2519
02:22:33,451 --> 02:22:34,550
- No, no.

2520
02:22:36,158 --> 02:22:38,090
Writers are strange characters.

2521
02:22:42,260 --> 02:22:46,880
There was a Magda in my
life, and I did love her,

2522
02:22:46,880 --> 02:22:47,730
when I was young.

2523
02:22:49,430 --> 02:22:51,910
Look, I wrote the play a long time ago,

2524
02:22:51,910 --> 02:22:56,910
it's too sentimental, but
there's something in it.

2525
02:23:00,705 --> 02:23:01,538
- Like Chekhov?

2526
02:23:04,680 --> 02:23:06,630
- I'm afraid I'm not much like Chekhov.

2527
02:23:08,085 --> 02:23:10,168
(laughs)

2528
02:23:11,373 --> 02:23:13,353
- What revered in Magda is, well,

2529
02:23:15,220 --> 02:23:17,800
